INSERT INTO `quiz_questions` VALUES (1,33,'What is the largest standard motherboard form factor?','Mini-ITX','Micro-ATX','ATX','E-ATX','D','E-ATX (Extended ATX) is the largest standard form factor, followed by ATX, Micro-ATX, and Mini-ITX.',1),(2,33,'What connects the CPU to the motherboard?','RAM slot','CPU socket','PCI Express','SATA port','B','The CPU socket on the motherboard holds the processor and provides electrical connections.',2),(3,33,'Which bus connects high-speed components like GPUs?','USB','SATA','PCI Express','PS/2','C','PCI Express (PCIe) is the high-speed expansion bus used for GPUs and other fast components.',3),(4,34,'What allows a CPU to handle multiple tasks?','Higher voltage','Context switching','Larger cache','More RAM','B','Context switching allows a CPU to rapidly switch between tasks, giving the illusion of multitasking.',1),(5,34,'What unit measures CPU speed?','Megabytes','Gigahertz (GHz)','Watts','Pixels','B','CPU clock speed is measured in GHz ‚Äî billions of cycles per second.',2),(6,35,'What happens to RAM contents when power is lost?','Data is saved to disk','Data persists for 24 hours','Data is lost (volatile)','Data is compressed','C','RAM is volatile ‚Äî all contents are lost when power is removed.',1),(7,35,'Which storage device has no moving parts?','HDD','Floppy disk','SSD','Tape drive','C','SSDs use flash memory with no moving parts, making them faster and more durable than HDDs.',2),(8,38,'How many bits are in one byte?','4','8','16','32','B','One byte consists of 8 bits.',1),(9,38,'What is the binary representation of decimal 10?','1000','1010','1100','1110','B','Decimal 10 = 8+2 = 1010 in binary.',2),(10,38,'What base does hexadecimal use?','Base 2','Base 8','Base 10','Base 16','D','Hexadecimal uses base 16 (0-9 and A-F).',3),(11,39,'What is the ASCII code for uppercase A?','41','65','97','48','B','The ASCII code for A is 65 (decimal) or 41 (hexadecimal).',1),(12,39,'How many characters can standard ASCII represent?','64','128','256','512','B','Standard ASCII uses 7 bits to represent 128 characters.',2),(13,40,'What character is used for Base64 padding?','#','*','=','&','C','Base64 uses the = sign for padding when the input length is not divisible by 3.',1),(14,40,'Is Base64 a form of encryption?','Yes, it is strong encryption','Yes, but weak encryption','No, it is encoding (reversible without a key)','No, it is hashing','C','Base64 is encoding, not encryption. Anyone can decode it without a key.',2),(15,41,'What are magic numbers in files?','Random encryption keys','Header bytes identifying file type','File size indicators','Version numbers','B','Magic numbers are the first few bytes of a file that identify its type regardless of extension.',1),(16,41,'What magic bytes identify a JPEG file?','50 4B 03 04','89 50 4E 47','FF D8 FF','47 49 46','C','JPEG files begin with the magic bytes FF D8 FF.',2),(17,42,'What does the AND gate output when both inputs are 1?','0','1','Undefined','Alternates','B','AND outputs 1 only when ALL inputs are 1.',1),(18,42,'Which gate outputs 1 when inputs differ?','AND','OR','XOR','NAND','C','XOR (exclusive OR) outputs 1 when inputs are different.',2),(19,42,'What is the opposite of an AND gate?','OR','NOT','NAND','XOR','C','NAND outputs the opposite of AND ‚Äî 0 only when both inputs are 1.',3),(20,43,'In XOR encryption, how do you decrypt?','Apply XOR with a different key','Apply XOR with the same key','Reverse the bits','Use the inverse key','B','XOR is its own inverse ‚Äî applying the same key decrypts the ciphertext.',1),(21,44,'What is the maximum file size on FAT32?','2 GB','4 GB','16 GB','Unlimited','B','FAT32 has a maximum individual file size of 4 GB.',1),(22,44,'Which file system supports permissions and encryption?','FAT32','exFAT','NTFS','EXT2','C','NTFS supports file permissions, encryption (EFS), and shadow copies.',2),(23,44,'What is the default file system for modern Linux?','NTFS','FAT32','EXT3','EXT4','D','EXT4 is the default file system for most modern Linux distributions.',3),(24,46,'Gmail is an example of which cloud model?','IaaS','PaaS','SaaS','On-premises','C','Gmail is Software as a Service ‚Äî you use the software without managing any infrastructure.',1),(25,46,'In IaaS, what does the provider manage?','Everything including applications','Physical hardware and networking','Only the operating system','Nothing','B','IaaS provides virtualized computing resources ‚Äî the provider manages physical hardware.',2),(26,47,'What part of the OS runs in protected memory?','Shell','Kernel','Desktop','Browser','B','The kernel operates in protected memory space to prevent user programs from corrupting core OS functions.',1),(27,47,'What signals the CPU to handle an event immediately?','A process','An interrupt','A thread','A driver','B','Interrupts (hardware or software) signal the CPU to pause current work and handle the event.',2),(28,47,'What initializes hardware before the OS loads?','Kernel','Shell','BIOS/UEFI','Desktop Manager','C','BIOS/UEFI firmware initializes hardware and hands control to the boot loader.',3),(29,49,'Which hypervisor type runs directly on hardware?','Type 1 (bare-metal)','Type 2 (hosted)','Type 3 (hybrid)','Type 4 (cloud)','A','Type 1 hypervisors run directly on hardware without a host OS (e.g., VMware ESXi).',1),(30,49,'VirtualBox is which type of hypervisor?','Type 1','Type 2','Type 3','Not a hypervisor','B','VirtualBox is a Type 2 (hosted) hypervisor that runs on top of an existing OS.',2),(31,52,'What is the default shell on most Linux systems?','zsh','fish','bash','csh','C','Bash (Bourne Again Shell) is the default shell on most Linux distributions.',1),(32,53,'What command runs a single command with root privileges?','su','sudo','root','admin','B','sudo runs a single command with elevated privileges without switching to the root user.',1),(33,53,'What is the UID of the root user?','1','0','1000','999','B','The root user always has UID 0 on Linux systems.',2),(34,55,'What numeric value represents rwxr-xr-x?','644','777','755','700','C','rwx(7) r-x(5) r-x(5) = 755.',1),(35,55,'What does the SUID bit do?','Deletes the file after execution','Runs the file with the owners privileges','Encrypts the file','Makes the file read-only','B','SUID (Set User ID) runs a program with the file owners permissions regardless of who executes it.',2),(36,56,'What does the PATH variable contain?','The current working directory','A list of directories searched for commands','The home directory path','The system hostname','B','PATH lists directories the shell searches when you type a command.',1),(37,60,'What flag copies directories recursively?','cp -f','cp -r','cp -a','cp -d','B','The -r flag copies directories and their contents recursively.',1),(38,60,'What does mkdir -p do?','Prompts before creating','Creates nested parent directories','Sets permissions','Moves directories','B','mkdir -p creates all necessary parent directories in the path.',2),(39,62,'Which command searches file contents for a pattern?','find','grep','which','locate','B','grep searches within file contents for matching text patterns.',1),(40,62,'Which command locates a binary in PATH?','find','grep','which','file','C','which shows the full path of a command binary found in PATH.',2),(41,64,'What command lists all running processes?','ls -all','ps aux','top -list','proc -a','B','ps aux lists all running processes with detailed information.',1),(42,65,'What does the pipe symbol (|) do?','Redirects output to a file','Sends output of one command as input to another','Runs commands in parallel','Creates a symbolic link','B','The pipe (|) sends the stdout of one command as stdin to the next command.',1),(43,65,'What does >> do vs >?','>> overwrites, > appends','>> appends, > overwrites','Both overwrite','Both append','B','> overwrites the file; >> appends to it.',2),(44,67,'What does SSH provide?','Unencrypted remote access','Encrypted remote access','File system encryption','Network monitoring','B','SSH provides encrypted remote terminal access over an insecure network.',1),(45,69,'What does site:example.com do in Google?','Creates a new site','Restricts results to that domain','Blocks that domain','Shows site statistics','B','The site: operator restricts search results to a specific domain.',1),(46,69,'What are Google Dorks?','Google employees','Clever searches that find unintended content','Google error pages','Encrypted search results','B','Google Dorks use advanced operators to find sensitive unintended content like passwords and cameras.',2),(47,72,'What HTTP method retrieves a resource?','POST','GET','PUT','DELETE','B','GET retrieves a resource from the server without modifying it.',1),(48,72,'What does HTTP status 404 mean?','Server error','Redirect','Not Found','OK','C','404 means the requested resource was not found on the server.',2),(49,72,'What port does HTTPS use by default?','80','8080','443','22','C','HTTPS uses port 443 by default; HTTP uses port 80.',3),(50,76,'What is the most common use of cookies?','Storing passwords','Session identification','Running scripts','Blocking ads','B','Cookies most commonly store session IDs to maintain login state across requests.',1),(51,76,'How much data can Local Storage hold per site?','1 KB','100 KB','5 MB','50 MB','C','Web Local Storage allows up to 5 MB of data per origin.',2),(52,78,'What device directs data to the correct port by MAC address?','Hub','Switch','Router','Modem','B','A switch directs data to the correct port based on the destination MAC address.',1),(53,78,'What is the main difference between a hub and a switch?','Hubs are faster','Switches send data to all ports','Hubs send data to all ports (broadcast)','There is no difference','C','Hubs broadcast data to all connected ports; switches direct data only to the destination port.',2),(54,79,'Which IP range is private?','8.8.8.0/24','192.168.0.0/16','1.1.1.0/24','216.58.0.0/16','B','192.168.0.0/16 is a private IP range reserved for lo